
Energy and Elements Produced by a Star

We know that nuclear energy powers our star because the other forms of energy (gravitational potential, chemical) are simply not energetic enough to sustain our star's luminosity for the amount of time that we know it has existed. 

Inside a nucleus, there are protons and neutrons. These inhabitants of the nucleus are called nucleons. Protons repel other protons due to the electromagnetic force, but attracted to all nucleons because of the strong nuclear force, which acts on a scale under $1 \text{ fm}$, a femtometer.

Proton-proton chains are responsible for most of the energy produced by stars with masses similar to that of the Sun. 

