2 How can two protons “melt” together?

The two relevant forces are the Coulomb force (electrostatic repulsion) and the strong nuclear force (nuclear attraction). In order for the two protons to be "melted together", the kinetic energy of a proton must overcome the Coulombian potential energy. 

$$

This kinetic energy is the same as thermal energy at this scale, so we can find the temperature required for the minimum thermal energy (and therefore kinetic energy) to overcome the Coulombian potential energy. 

$$

In the core of the sun, we have $T_\text{Sun} \approx 1.5 \cdot 10^7 \text{ K}$, so the process seems impossible. However, this is the average kinetic energy of the protons in the sun, so even if the average temperature is only that of $T_\text{Sun}$, some protons will have individually much higher temperature. The tail end of this distribution of kinetic energies will be able to overcome the Coulombian potential energy. Once this potential energy is overcome, the strong force takes over. 

Another reason (the main reason, in fact) that fusion can take place despite the relatively low temperature of the sun, is explained by quantum tunnelling. Protons described by quantum mechanics follows the behaviour of a wave, so each proton has an assosciated wavelength $\lambda = h / p$, where $h$ is the Planck constant and $p$ is the momentum. By solving the Schrodinger equation TODO-REVIEW. This quantum effect is the main contributor to fusion. 

3 PPI Chain

Explain the PPI chain, with some details on the “reagents” and the “products”, but without numbers by heart.

Once two protons interact very energetically and with the aid of quantum behaviour, like in the core of a star, they fuse together to form an nucleus of deuterium. This nucleus consists of one proton and one neutron (two protons would be unstable) and they emit a positron and a neutrino. 

$$

The fusion of the two protons are slightly more massive than the deuterium, and this extra mass is converted into kinetic energy for the positron and the neutrino. Once the positron encounters an electron, the two particles annihilate, producing energy equal to their mass, in the form of a gamma ray. The total energy emitted in this reaction is $Q=1.44 \text{ MeV}$, which includes the kinetic energy converted from mass ($0.42 \text{ MeV}$) and the gamma ray from annihilation ($1.02 \text{ MeV}$). The neutrino also has mass and energy but it doesn't interact with anything, so that energy is considered wasted ($0.26 \text{ MeV}$).

The lifetime of such a reaction is defined as the probability that that event happens, so a longer lifetime essentially means more waiting between this event happening. The lifetime of this reaction is $1.4 \cdot 10^{10} \text{ years}$, which is a very long time, but considering that there are about $10^{57}$ protons in the sun, it happens quite often. 

$$

The deuterium nucleus interacts with another proton, producing helium-3 and a gamma ray. 

$$

After this, two helium-3 nuclei interact to produce helium-4, the regular helium, and they emit two other protons. Guess what those protons will go on to do. $Q = 5.49 \text{ MeV}$, $\text{lifetime} = 1.5 \text{ sec}$. 

$$

This interaction produces energy in the form of gamma rays, neutrinos, and positron, and a helium nucleus. The binding energy of this configuration is higher with respect to the beginning. $Q = 12.86 \text{ MeV}$, $\text{lifetime} = 1 \text{ My}$. 

So in total, for a PPI chain, the totally available energy is the first two steps doubled (because there have to be two ${}^3\text{He}$ nuclei for the third step to occur) summed with the third step. 

