$$

With $\text{lifetime} = 1 \text{ sec}$, $Q = 10.8 \text{MeV}$. The positron $e^+$ is almost immediately annihilated with another electron, giving rise to two gamma rays, totalling the aforementioned $1.02 \text{ MeV}$, while the neutrino $\nu_\text{e}$ takes $7.2 \text{ MeV}$. The beryllium-8 follows the same fate of decaying into two helium-4 nuclei. 

6 The CNO Cycle and the Production of Carbon

Proton-proton chains are not the only way of “producing” energy in stars. For stars much more massive than the Sun ($T> 16 \text{ MK}$), the CNO cycle takes place. 

You start with a nucleus of carbon-12, a series of reactions involving protons take place, and at the end, you arrive at carbon-12 again but in the mean time you have produced a helium-4 nucleus worth of energy again. 



Similar to proton-proton chains, a nucleus of helium is produced, but here it is with a catalyst of carbon-12. A higher temperature allows for these processes to proceed faster, but the CNO cycle and the proton-proton chains are not mutually exclusive. The CNO cycle is much less important in colder stars, like our sun, but it still happens, just like proton-proton chains do happen in hotter stars. In our sun, the energy is produced mainly by PPI chains. 

• PPI: $56\%$

• PPII: $40\%$

• PPIII: $0.05\%$

• CNO: $3.2\%$

But where does carbon-12 come from in this case? The 3-alpha process, which requires a temperature greater than $10^8 \text{ K}$, meaning it is completely absent in our sun. We will briefly talk about the 3-alpha process here and then talk about how our Sun creates carbon-12 despite not being able to do the 3-alpha process. 

